═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
[SECTION 9] SUMMARY - KEY TAKEAWAYS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. TWO SEPARATE PANELS:
   ├─ Panel 1 (Primary): Blue sidebar, 280px, always visible
   └─ Panel 2 (Secondary): White sidebar, 260px, conditional

2. PANEL 1 SHOWS:
   ├─ User profile
   ├─ Main navigation
   ├─ All memberships (categorized)
   └─ Account settings

3. PANEL 2 SHOWS:
   ├─ Contextual sub-navigation
   ├─ Membership-specific links
   └─ Quick access to sections

4. THE "COLLAPSE" IS NOT A COLLAPSE:
   ├─ It's a page navigation
   ├─ Different pages have different CSS rules
   ├─ Panel 2 visibility controlled by page ID
   └─ No JavaScript collapse animation

5. VISIBILITY RULES:
   ├─ Main dashboard (/dashboard): Panel 1 visible, Panel 2 hidden
   ├─ Membership pages: Both panels visible (desktop only)
   └─ Mobile: Only Panel 1 (slides in), Panel 2 always hidden

6. CSS CONTROL:
   ├─ .page-id-401190 .dashboard__content-sidebar { display: none; }
   ├─ This rule hides Panel 2 on main dashboard
   └─ Other pages don't have this class, so Panel 2 shows

7. RESPONSIVE:
   ├─ Desktop (1280px+): Both panels can be visible
   ├─ Tablet (768-1279px): Only Panel 1 (via menu button)
   └─ Mobile (<768px): Only Panel 1 (via menu button)

8. USER FLOW:
   Login → Main Dashboard (Panel 1 only)
   → Click Membership → Membership Page (Both panels)
   → Navigate within membership (Both panels stay)
   → Return to dashboard (Panel 2 disappears)

